article.description: Allison Feaster scored 17 points as the host Charlotte Sting built a 17-point lead, then held off the Minnesota Lynx for a 76-72 victory Friday night.
article.headline: Charlotte shoots 57 percent vs. Minnesota
article.linkText: Feaster's big night helps Sting snap streak
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Allison Feaster scored 17 points as the Charlotte Sting built a 17-point lead, then held off the Minnesota Lynx for a 76-72 victory Friday night.

Feaster had three 3-pointers and was 6-for-8 from the field as the Sting (6-4) ended a two-game losing streak.

Tammy Sutton-Brown added 13 points and seven rebounds and Andrea Stinson and Dawn Staley scored 11 points apiece for Charlotte, which was 12-of-18 from the field in the second half.

The Sting shot 57 percent (25-for-44), the highest field-goal percentage ever allowed by the Lynx (4-6). Minnesota -- the WNBA's worst defensive team -- had allowed 55 percent shooting twice, including June 6 by New York.

Tamika Williams scored 16 points for Minnesota, which has lost three straight and five of six. Katie Smith added 14 points on 5-of-14 shooting.

Feaster hit a 3-pointer 10 seconds into the second half to begin a 17-7 run. Staley's layup on a behind-the-back feed from Stinson put Charlotte ahead 51-34 with 12 minutes left.

The Lynx cut the lead to 70-67 on Smith's 3-pointer with 37 seconds left. The Sting then threw the ball away on the inbounds pass -- one of their 20 turnovers in the game. Smith then missed a 3-point attempt that could have tied the score.

Staley and Feaster then combined to go 6-of-6 from the free-throw line over the final 22 seconds.

Charlotte, which never trailed, led 32-23 at halftime in beating Minnesota for the fourth straight time dating to the 2001 season.
